Exploratory Analysis of Seattle Collisions

Leah Erb

This report explores collision report data from Seattle, Washington, USA.

The Dataset

The Seattle Collisions dataset is a compilation of over 200,000 collision reports created by Seattle Police Department (SPD) that were then recorded by Seattle Department of Transportation (SDOT), between the years 2004 and 2018.

Load data

datafile = '../data/collisions_clean.rda'
load(file = datafile)

# Create df_trim_yrs to contain only complete year's worth of data
# TODO: include logic, remove hardcode
df_full_yrs <- subset(df, year != '2019' & year != '2003')
df$hour <- as.integer(df$hour)

When

1. Collision count by year

ggplot(data = df_full_yrs %>% count(year), aes(x = year, y = n)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = n)) + 
    labs(title = 'Collision count by year', x = '', y = '') +
    mytheme_minimal +
    scale_fill_distiller(palette = 'Greys', direction = 1) +
    scale_x_discrete(position = 'top') +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)

Observations: There appears to be a 10-is year trend: 5 years down, 5 years up, then going back down.

The first peak, at year 2005, was higher than the second peak 10 years later, at year 2015.

I had expected to see a steady increase in Seattle collisions, mirroring population growth. Perhaps Im wrong about the steady increase in population, or wrong that the number of reported collisions have a strong correlation with the population. #TODO: import population data and compare rate changes with collision rates by year.

2b. Collision count by hour, Radial version

create_radial_plot <- function(data, col_name, title, subtitle) {
    
    col_name <- enquo(col_name)
    
    # define inner and outer circle sizes (y)
    max_col <- as.integer(
        data %>%
            group_by(!!col_name) %>%
            summarise(n = n()) %>%
            top_n(1) %>%
            .$n)
    # size the hole for the middle of radial at 5% of the radius
    donut_hole <- max_col * .05  
    # define y values for reference circles at 1/3 intervals
    b1 <- max_col * .33
    b2 <- max_col * .66
    b3 <- max_col * .99
 
    p <- ggplot() +
        # make radial
        coord_polar(start=-48/360) +
        # add circle grid lines at defined breaks
        geom_hline(yintercept = c(0, b1, b2, b3), colour = my_grid_grey, size = 0.2) +
        # draw radius grid manually to avoid extending beyond outer circle
        geom_vline(xintercept = seq(0, 23), colour = my_grid_grey, size = 0.2) +
        # draw data 'slices'
        geom_bar(data = data, aes(x = hour), width=1, color='white', size=0.1)  +
        # mark hours on the 24-hour clock
        scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,23), 
                           labels = c('12 am', paste(1:11,'am'), '12 pm', paste(13:23-12, 'pm'))) +
        # make donut hole
        scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-donut_hole, max_col + donut_hole)) + 
        # add plot titles
        labs(title = title,
             subtitle = subtitle,
             caption = 'Data source: https://data.seattle.gov  (2004 - 2018)') +
        # define theme options
        theme_minimal() +
        theme(
            plot.title = element_text(size = 24, face = 'bold', color = '#333333'),
            plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, color = '#333333'),
            plot.caption = element_text(size = 7), #, hjust = 1.8),
            # bold-ize 6 am/pm and 12 am/pm
            axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12,
                                       face = c('bold', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain',
                                                'bold', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain',
                                                'bold', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain',
                                                'bold', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain', 'plain')),
            # remove axis labels
            axis.title = element_blank(),
            # remove y axis ticks and text
            axis.text.y = element_blank() , 
            axis.ticks = element_blank(),
            # remove outermost circle
            panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
            # remove 1/2 hour grid lines
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            # remove hour grid lines, too
            panel.grid.major.x = element_blank()
        )  
 
    
    return (p)
}
# grideline grey setting
my_grid_grey <- 'grey90'
# All collisions
create_radial_plot(data = df, 
            col_name = hour,
            title = '', 
            subtitle = 'All collisions')

# DUI
create_radial_plot(data = df[which(df$DUI == 'Y'),], 
            col_name = hour,
            title = '', 
            subtitle = 'DUIs')

Observations: Collisions tend to rise during commute hours, starting at the lowest point around 4am, reaching a peak at 5pm.

2a. Hourly collisions by day of week

weekend <- c('Saturday', 'Sunday')
weekday <- c('Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday')
alldays <- c(weekday, weekend)

# TODO fix y max limit programmatically
plot_hours <- function(day, title) {
    gg <- ggplot(data = df %>%
               filter(!is.na(hour) & weekdays(INCDATE) %in% day) %>%
               count(hour),
           aes(x = hour, y = n, group = 1 )) +
        geom_line() +
        labs(title = paste(title), x = '', y = '') +
        mytheme_minimal  +
        scale_x_discrete(breaks = c(0,4,8,12,16,20,24)) +
        scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 2250), 
                           breaks = seq(0, 2100, 700),
                           labels = scales::comma) 
    return (gg)
}

# create list of plots, one for each day of the week
plot_list <- lapply(
    as.list(alldays), function(x){
    plot_hours(x, paste0('- ', x, 's'))
})

#cowplot::plot_grid(plotlist = plot_list, ncol = 3)

ggarrange(plotlist = plot_list, ncol=3, nrow=3) + 
    annotate(geom = 'text', label = 'title', hjust = 0)
